  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Verifying Missing Details**\n\nI\'ve just made a quick check to ensure we\'re not overlooking any critical details. Right now, I\'m specifically confirming our system guidelines. It looks like the environment variables are correctly defined (`GEMINI_API_KEY` and `APP_URL`), so we\'re good there.\n\n\n**Reviewing Configuration Details**\n\nOkay, I\'ve confirmed that the setup includes the custom variable we implemented. I\'ve also verified the server-side API route configuration (`/api/*`) for API key protection, ensuring our Gemini API key is hidden. Plus, the system adheres to the \"no custom UI for API keys\" guideline. Port 3000 is still hardcoded. We also updated metadata.json and configured the necessary dependencies and styling.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I have completed building the **Coral Name Generator** application. Following full-stack architectural guidelines, this application handles file uploads, processes image content securely on the server-side via the latest **Gemini 3.5 Flash** model, and bundles structured outputs into a professionally styled Excel spreadsheet complete with embedded high-resolution photos.\n\nHere is a summary of the design and implementation details:\n\n### \360\237\216\250 Visual & User Experience Design\n- **Subtle Deep-Sea Palette**: Formulated an immersive dark ocean backdrop using slate, deep-blue, and navy hues, with bright coral-pink (`rose`), fluorescent yellow-green, and sea-foam teal accents representing coral fluorescence under actinic lighting.\n- **Custom Typography Pairing**: Integrated **Plus Jakarta Sans** for display headings and body copy to convey a clean, premium, modern appearance, combined with **JetBrains Mono** for specifications and status badges.\n- **Fluid & Responsive Layout**: The interface adjusts dynamically across all devices, featuring subtle entrance and transition animations powered by `motion` for state transitions and pending image grids.\n- **Dual-Action Upload Zone**: Implemented a modern drag-and-drop file uploader that seamlessly supports dropping folders/files or clicking to browse via file explorer, displaying file size metrics and thumbnail previews.\n\n### \342\232\231\357\270\217 Core Technical Capabilities\n- **Concurrently Proxied Server-Side AI Analysis**: \n  - To secure secret keys, the frontend sends base64 payloads to the `/api/generate-coral-names` Express route.\n  - The server utilizes the modern `@google/genai` SDK and the powerful `gemini-3.5-flash` model.\n  - Multiple coral photos are analyzed **concurrently in parallel** using `Promise.all` for rapid classification, generating creative trade names, scientific names, recommended aquarium placement, care complexity levels, and optimal light/flow specifications through strict JSON schema constraints.\n- **Interactive Review Dashboard**: \n  - Users can review the generated classifications and easily edit names, species, care levels, or descriptions directly in a unified form before generating their final excel spreadsheet.\n  - They can also remove specimens from the batch.\n- **Embedded Image Excel Generator (`exceljs`)**:\n  - The server handles Excel creation via `exceljs` under `/api/export-excel`.\n  - Columns are carefully proportioned and formatted with a sleek Slate-900 header row and gridlines enabled.\n  - Generates the Excel file with images embedded directly into the cells in Column A. It automatically calculates row dimensions (setting row height to `100pt`) so photos render cleanly without distortion.\n- **Resilient & Lazy Initialization**:\n  - Leverages lazy-loading patterns to avoid app crashes if environment variables are unconfigured.\n  - Provides intuitive loading states and reassurance messages for larger batches of media.\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 2
      nanos: 315040458
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
