  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Refining Retry Logic**\n\nI\'m now focusing on improving the retry mechanism, specifically for 503 errors. Initial thoughts centered on fine-tuning, but I\'m pausing to re-examine the error response details, which could yield insights for a more targeted enhancement. It seems high load is a factor.\n\n\n**Inspecting Error Properties**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on a critical oversight in how we handle errors. The stringification of the error object might be overly simplistic. It looks like `JSON.stringify` could be masking important error details specific to `ApiError`, like \"UNAVAILABLE\" or \"high demand,\" because of how error properties are typically handled. I\'m now digging into the `ApiError` properties themselves to see if they\'re being missed.\n\n\n**Developing Robust Error Detection**\n\nI\'m now implementing a more thorough error detection method. My focus has shifted to extracting every possible detail, including `message`, `status`, `code`, `statusCode`, `name`, `stack`, and any nested `error` objects via `JSON.stringify`. A utility is coming together to capture the full picture, ensuring no critical information is lost during analysis.\n\n\n**Optimizing Error Serialization**\n\nI\'ve significantly refined the error serialization process. I\'m now leveraging `Object.getOwnPropertyNames` to capture all properties, even non-enumerable ones, for inclusion in the error string. This approach ensures a comprehensive representation of the error object, including all the error\'s data, regardless of visibility, which I\'m converting to lowercase to simplify comparisons.\n\n\n**Implementing Request Staggering**\n\nI\'m now focusing on request distribution to avoid rate limiting. Initial ideas involve increasing retry attempts and adding jitter, but I\'ve pivoted to implementing a dynamic initial delay based on image index. Specifically, I\'m setting an initial delay of `index * 500` milliseconds to stagger request execution and distribute load more effectively. This addresses the potential thundering herd effect of concurrent image analysis.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 12
      nanos: 945672806
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
